---
description: Never put /** @type or any @tag JSDoc inside constructors or function bodies
alwaysApply: true
---

# No inline JSDoc inside constructors or functions

**`/** @type { ... } */` and all other `@` tags are banned inside constructors, methods, loops, and callbacks.** Not "prefer less." Not "only when needed." **Never.**

Module-level `@typedef` for cross-boundary shapes is fine. One-line prose (no `@` tags) is fine. Everything else inside `{ }` blocks is not.

## Constructors — especially

Do not annotate `this`, locals, or params inside a `constructor`:

```javascript
// ❌ NEVER
constructor(grid) {
    /** @type {Map<number, Hop[]>} */
    this.hops = new Map();
    /** @type {import("./Foo.js").Foo | null} */
    this._foo = null;
}

// ✅ JUST WRITE THE CODE
constructor(grid) {
    this.hops = new Map();
    this._foo = null;
}
```

## Any function body — same rule

```javascript
// ❌ NEVER
function bake() {
    /** @type {Int32Array} */
    const offsets = new Int32Array(size);
    for (const item of items) {
        /** @type {number} */
        let write = 0;
    }
}

// ✅ NEVER ADD @type TO "FIX" INFERENCE — USE PLAIN JS
function bake() {
    const offsets = new Int32Array(size);
    let write = 0;
}
```

## If an agent adds it

Remove it in the same pass. Do not refactor the surrounding code to "justify" the annotation. Do not replace inner `@type` with inner `@param`. Delete the comment block.

See also `jsdoc-minimal.mdc` for the full JSDoc policy.
